        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>SENSITIVITY: 
Observations of 4 molecular outflows in ULIRGs by Cicone et al. (2013; ASTROPH/1311.2595) have shown that the spatial extent of their molecular outflow is 1-2kpc. At the distance of IRAS 20100-4156 (z=0.13) this amounts to 0.45-0.9 arcsec. In order not to spread the high-velocity CO(1-0) flux over more than one beam we request a resolution of 1.5".
In order to estimate the RMS sensitivity needed to detect the high-velocity wings in the CO(1-0) profile of IRAS 20100, we need an estimate of the expected CO(1-0) intensity in these wings. We will assume that the integrated intensity in the CO(1-0) line wings is proportional to the equivalent width of the OH 119 micron line divided by the square of the distance (or in other words: the CO outflow luminosity is assumed to be proportional to the OH outflow mass). We determine the proportionality factor from the average observed relation in Mrk231, IRAS 08572 and IRAS 10565. This method was successfully applied to infer the sensitivity needed for our PdBI observations of IRAS 03158.
We therefore expect the high-velocity wings of the CO(1-0) line to have a flux density of 0.5mJy over a 800 km/s velocity range outside the CO core (-200 to +200 km/s). To obtain S/N=5 in 100 km/s bins we hence require an RMS of 0.1mJy, assuming that the source is comfortably contained within one beam. If the CO outflow is slightly extended, the above S/N requirement will at least assure detection.


IMAGING:
The two colliding galaxies that constitute IRAS 20100-4156 span about 7"x7" judging from an I-band optical image. This fits comfortably within the inner 1/3 of the primary beam. 
A lower spectral resolution than 1.5" (needed to confine the high-velocity outflow to one beam) would unnecessarily limit the spatial information we can extract for this close galaxy pair which has a nuclear separation of 3".


CORRELATOR SETUP: We want to be able to detect CO(1-0) line emission in 100 km/s bins over a velocity range of -2000 km/s to + 2000 km/s around the CO line center, even though we don't expect to see emission at velocities exceeding 1000 km/s to the red or blue. This should be easily achievable within a bandwidth of 5508 km/s centered on the redshifted CO line center at 102.04604 GHz. We choose a spectral resolution of 2.869 km/s which can be easily rebinned to 100 km/s to achieve our RMS goal.

CALIBRATION: default.

BANDPASS ACCURACY: nominal.

SCHEDULING/TIME CONSTRAINTS: no constraints.

DATA RATE: nominal.

SPECIAL CONSTRAINTS: none.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
